    <title>Combined summary - On Rewriting Bitcoin (was Re: [Libbitcoin] Satoshi client: is a fork past 0.10 possible?)</title>
    <updated>2023-06-09T17:24:43.406500+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-February/007468.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>This context contains several email exchanges and discussions related to Bitcoin development. One of the discussions is about the creation of a stand-alone libconsensus library. Tamas Blummer argues that it cannot be separated from Bitcoin Core's consensus critical code due to its criticality and legacy design. However, he focuses on innovation that uses the Core as a border router for the blockchain.Another conversation is about the creation of Java bindings for lib consensus. It was suggested that Swig could be used as a tool for generating automated Java bindings that can also be adjusted for other languages. The importance of maintaining strict consensus between Bitcoin Core versions was also discussed, as well as the need for formal proofs of correctness for the existing implementation.There were criticisms regarding the lack of transparency in the soft-forking process for Bitcoin, with Peter Todd urging the Bitcoin Core team to move the consensus critical code out of Bitcoin Core and into a standalone libconsensus library. Troy Benjegerdes recommended looking at the git commit history for the consensus-critical part of the Bitcoin Core codebase, as much work has been done in cleaning it up and refactoring for v0.10.0/libconsensus.Finally, there is mention of the Lighthouse project initiated by Tamas Blummer aimed at integrating Java language binding to lib consensus. The proposed language binding would allow JVM application developers to innovate without raising concerns about network forks through incompatible alternate protocol implementations. This project is seen as an alternative to the border router setup. Overall, the email exchanges provide insights into the challenges and innovations in Bitcoin development.</summary>
